example.p:
Solving the homogeneous system (- I - H) \uvec{x} = \zerovec leads to
 E_{-1}(H) = \Span \left\{ \left[\begin{array}{r} -\ci \\ \ci \\ 1 \end{array}\right] \right\} .
Solving the homogeneous system (2 I - H) \uvec{x} = \zerovec leads to

	E_2(H) = \Span \left\{
		\begin{bmatrix} \ci \\ 0 \\ 1 \end{bmatrix},
		\begin{bmatrix} 1 \\ 1 \\ 0 \end{bmatrix}
	\right\}
.
Notice that the basis vector for E_{-1}(H) is already orthogonal to each of the basis vectors for E_2(H),
as expected.
But the basis for E_2(H) is not orthogonal,
so we will need to apply the  process to those two vectors.
Labelling those two vectors as \uvec{v}_1 and \uvec{v}_2,
we may keep \uvec{e}_1 = \uvec{v}_1,
but we must adjust

	\uvec{e}_2
	= \uvec{v}_2 - \frac{\inprod{\uvec{v}_2}{\uvec{e}_1}}{\norm{\uvec{e}_1}^2} \, \uvec{e}_1
	= \begin{bmatrix} 1 \\ 1 \\ 0 \end{bmatrix}
	- \frac{- \ci}{2} \begin{bmatrix} \ci \\ 0 \\ 1 \end{bmatrix}
	= \begin{bmatrix} \frac{1}{2} \\ 1 \\ \frac{\ci}{2} \end{bmatrix}
.
We now have an orthogonal set of eigenvectors which we can normalize to obtain an orthonormal set

	\left\{
		\frac{1}{\sqrt{3}} \left[\begin{array}{r} -\ci \\ \ci \\ 1 \end{array}\right],
		\frac{1}{\sqrt{2}} \begin{bmatrix} \ci \\ 0 \\ 1 \end{bmatrix},
		\frac{1}{\sqrt{6}} \begin{bmatrix} 1 \\ 2 \\ \ci \end{bmatrix}
	\right\}
.

Finally, taking U to be the unitary matrix with these orthonormal vectors as columns

	U = \frac{\sqrt{6}}{6}
	\begin{bmatrix}
		-\ci \sqrt{2} \amp   \ci \sqrt{3} \amp  1 \\
		 \ci \sqrt{2} \amp       0        \amp  2 \\
		 \sqrt{2}     \amp     \sqrt{3}   \amp \ci
	\end{bmatrix}

allows us to unitarily digaonalize H:
 \inv{U} H U = \adjoint{U} H U = \begin{bmatrix} -1 \\ \amp 2 \\ \amp \amp 2 \end{bmatrix} .

Let's apply  to the normal matrix

	N = \begin{bmatrix}
	 2 + \ci \amp 1 - \ci \amp  1 + \ci \\
	 1 - \ci \amp 2 + \ci \amp -1 - \ci \\
	-1 - \ci \amp 1 + \ci \amp  2 + \ci
	\end{bmatrix}
.
But first, let's verify that it is normal:


		\adjoint{N} N
		\amp =
		\begin{bmatrix}
			 2 + \ci \amp 1 - \ci \amp  1 + \ci \\
			 1 - \ci \amp 2 + \ci \amp -1 - \ci \\
			-1 - \ci \amp 1 + \ci \amp  2 + \ci
		\end{bmatrix}
		\begin{bmatrix}
			2 - \ci \amp  1 + \ci \amp -1 + \ci \\
			1 + \ci \amp  2 - \ci \amp  1 - \ci \\
			1 - \ci \amp -1 + \ci \amp  2 - \ci
		\end{bmatrix}

		\amp
		= \begin{bmatrix}
		9 \amp 0 \amp 0 \\
		0 \amp 0 \amp 9 \\
		0 \amp 0 \amp 9
		\end{bmatrix}
		\text{,}

		N \adjoint{N}
		\amp =
		\begin{bmatrix}
			2 - \ci \amp  1 + \ci \amp -1 + \ci \\
			1 + \ci \amp  2 - \ci \amp  1 - \ci \\
			1 - \ci \amp -1 + \ci \amp  2 - \ci
		\end{bmatrix}
		\begin{bmatrix}
			 2 + \ci \amp 1 - \ci \amp  1 + \ci \\
			 1 - \ci \amp 2 + \ci \amp -1 - \ci \\
			-1 - \ci \amp 1 + \ci \amp  2 + \ci
		\end{bmatrix}

		\amp = \begin{bmatrix}
			9 \amp 0 \amp 0 \\
			0 \amp 0 \amp 9 \\
			0 \amp 0 \amp 9
		\end{bmatrix}
		\text{.}


The characteristic polynomial is  c_N(\lambda) = (\lambda - 3)^2 (\lambda - 3 \ci) ,
so the eigenvalues are \lambda_1 = 3, \lambda_2 = 3 \ci.

Solving the homogeneous system (3 I - N) \uvec{x} = \zerovec leads to

	E_3(N) = \Span \left\{
		\begin{bmatrix} \ci \\ 0 \\ 1 \end{bmatrix},
		\begin{bmatrix} 1 \\ 1 \\ 0 \end{bmatrix}
	\right\}
.
Solving the homogeneous system (3 I - N) \uvec{x} = \zerovec leads to
 E_{3 \ci}(N) = \Span \left\{ \left[\begin{array}{r} -\ci \\ \ci \\ 1 \end{array}\right] \right\} .

Finally, taking U to be the unitary matrix with these orthonormal vectors as columns

	U = \frac{1}{\sqrt{6}}
	\begin{bmatrix}
		\ci \sqrt{3} \amp  1  \amp -\ci \sqrt{2} \\
		     0       \amp  2  \amp  \ci \sqrt{2} \\
		  \sqrt{3}   \amp \ci \amp    \sqrt{2}
	\end{bmatrix}

allows us to unitarily digaonalize N:
 \inv{U} N U = \adjoint{U} N U = \begin{bmatrix} 3 \\ \amp 3 \\ \amp \amp 3 \ci \end{bmatrix} .
